[src:dpkg/dpkg-1-en] To install a package, you first need to find it in an archive or CDROM.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-1-en] Note that this will not actually install or remove anything, but just set the selection state on the requested packages.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-1-en] You will need some other application to actually download and install the requested packages.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-1-en] For example, run **apt-get dselect-upgrade**.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-1-en] Ordinarily, you will find that dselect(1) provides a more convenient way to modify the package selection states.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-1-en] Additional functionality can be gained by installing any of the following packages: **apt**, **aptitude** and **debsums**.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Use **dpkg** to install and remove packages from your system.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] You can also invoke **dpkg-deb** by calling **dpkg** with whatever options you want to pass to **dpkg-deb**.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] **dpkg** will spot that you wanted **dpkg-deb** and run it for you.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] For most commands taking an input archive argument, the archive can be read from standard input if the archive name is given as a single minus character («**-**»); otherwise lack of support will be documented in their respective command description.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] subdirectory, which contains the control information files such as the control file itself.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] appear in the binary package's filesystem archive, but instead the files in it will be put in the binary package's control information area.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Unless you specify **--nocheck**, **dpkg-deb** will read **DEBIAN/control** and parse it.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] It will check the file for syntax errors and other problems, and display the name of the binary package being built.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] **dpkg-deb** will also check the permissions of the maintainer scripts and other files found in the **DEBIAN** control information directory.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If no *archive* is specified then **dpkg-deb** will write the package into the file *binary-directory***.deb**.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If the archive to be created already exists it will be overwritten.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Provides information about a binary package archive.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If no *control-file-name*s are specified then it will print a summary of the contents of the package as well as its control file.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If any *control-file-name*s are specified then **dpkg-deb** will print them in the order they were specified; if any of the components weren't present it will print an error message to stderr about each one and exit with status 2.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] The default format displays the package's name and version on one line, separated by a tabulator.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Extracts control file information from a binary package archive.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If no *control-field-name*s are specified then it will print the whole control file.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If any are specified then **dpkg-deb** will print their contents, in the order in which they appear in the control file.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] If more than one *control-field-name* is specified then **dpkg-deb** will precede each with its field name (and a colon and space).
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] No errors are reported for fields requested but not found.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Lists the contents of the filesystem tree archive portion of the package archive.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Extracts the filesystem tree from a package archive into the specified directory.
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] Note that extracting a package to the root directory will *not* result in a correct installation!
[src:dpkg/dpkg-deb-1-en] ) which prints a listing of the files extracted as it goes.
