[src:dpkg/dpkg] `dpkg` (Debian Package) itself is a low-level tool.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] Advanced Package Tool (APT), a higher-level tool, is more commonly used than `dpkg` as it can fetch packages from remote locations and deal with complex package relations, such as dependency resolution.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] Frontends for APT, like aptitude (ncurses) and synaptic (GTK), are used for their user-friendly interfaces.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] The Debian package *dpkg* provides the `dpkg` program, and several other programs needed for runtime functioning of the packaging system, including `dpkg-deb`, `dpkg-split`, `dpkg-query`, `dpkg-statoverride`, `dpkg-divert` and `dpkg-trigger`.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] It also includes the programs such as `update-alternatives` and `start-stop-daemon`.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] The Debian package "dpkg-dev" includes the many build tools described below.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] The first attempt at a package management system for Linux was possibly the development of StopAlop by Greg Wettstein at the Roger Maris Cancer Center in Fargo, North Dakota.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] It provided inspiration to create dpkg. dpkg was originally created by Ian Murdock in January 1994 as a Shell script.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] Matt Welsh, Carl Streeter and Ian Murdock then rewrote it in Perl, and then later the main part was rewritten in C by Ian Jackson in 1994.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] The name *dpkg* was originally a shortening of *Debian package*, but the meaning of that phrase has evolved significantly, as dpkg the software is orthogonal to the deb package format and the Debian Policy Manual which defines how Debian packages behave in Debian.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] dpkg-dev contains a series of development tools needed to unpack, build, and upload Debian source code packages.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] The dpkg source package also contains *dselect*, a frontend software.
[src:dpkg/dpkg] The `install-info` program used to be included in the dpkg software package, but was later removed as it became developed and distributed separately, as part of GNU Texinfo.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:dpkg/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:dpkg/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
